   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>The Little Orchard</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Shoreham</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Kent</addrLine>
               </address>

               <dateline>
                  <date when="1913-11-20"> Nov 20.</date>
               </dateline>

               <salute>My dear friend.</salute>
            </opener>

            <milestone xml:id="m01" unit="section"/>

            <p>How nice of you to write to me from <placeName ref="#pl:Cambridge"
                  >Cambridge</placeName>! and thank you too for telling me that you are pleased to
               have this link with <persName ref="#ps:ArthurHenniker">Arthur</persName> in belonging
               to his old College. <placeName ref="#pl:MagdaleneCambridge">Magdalene</placeName>
               must be proud to have <hi rend="underline">you</hi> as a Fellow. I hope it may be
               cheering to you, &amp; a real interest, to go there from time to time.</p>

            <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_2.jpg"/>

            <milestone xml:id="m02" unit="section"/>

            <p>I see in to-day's "<orgName type="newspaper" ref="#ps:DailyMail"
                        ><choice><abbr>D</abbr><expan>Daily</expan></choice>Mail</orgName>" an
               account of the "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1887_Woodlanders">Woodlanders</ref>" &amp; a
               picture of <persName ref="#ps:MartySouth">Marty South</persName>. It will be
               interesting to hear how far you –, (for perhaps you saw the <hi rend="underline"
                  >Rehearsals</hi>, at any rate?) &amp; <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Miss
                  Dugdale</persName>, think she came <del>up</del> near to your conception of the
               character? It <choice><abbr>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>would</expan></choice> rather wonderful if an <hi rend="underline"
                  >untrained</hi> actress succeeded in satisfying <pb n="3"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_3.jpg"/>
               <milestone xml:id="m03" unit="section"/> people who care for the book. I daresay
                  <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Miss D.</persName> will kindly write &amp; tell
               me about it. –</p>

            <p> I am going to send you a very small
                  <choice><abbr>vol.</abbr><expan>volume</expan></choice> of really charming poems
               by <persName ref="#ps:MillicentWedmore">Miss Wedmore</persName>. I think "<name
                  type="poem">England</name>" &amp; "<name type="poem">The Grand Duke's
                  Funeral</name>" <hi rend="underline">especially</hi> good. I hope she will have
               the praise she deserves from some of the critics. <persName
                  ref="#ps:FrederickWedmore">Sir F. Wedmore</persName> gave a <pb n="4"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_4.jpg"/>
               <milestone xml:id="m04" unit="section"/>
               <milestone xml:id="m05" unit="section"/>
               <milestone xml:id="m06" unit="section"/> very interesting poetry <hi rend="underline"
                  >reading</hi> the other <choice><abbr>evg.</abbr><expan>evening</expan></choice>
               in <placeName ref="#pl:Sevenoaks">Sevenoaks</placeName>. He read <hi rend="underline"
                  >your</hi> "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1890_Bereft">Bereft"</ref> &amp; "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1902_TheRashBride">The Rash Bride</ref>" - (The latter <hi
                  rend="underline">particularly</hi> well - I thought. Also a beautiful little poem
                  "<name type="poem">Twilight</name>", by <persName ref="#ps:JohnMasefield"
                  >Masefield</persName>, which I am sure
                     <choice><abbr>wd.</abbr><expan>would</expan></choice> appeal to <hi
                  rend="underline">you</hi> – &amp; a lovely little lyric "<name type="poem">Denny's
                  Daughter</name>", by <persName ref="#ps:MoiraONeill">Moira O'Neill</persName> –
               intensely pathetic in its simplicity. Do you know it? I wonder if you are writing
               more verse now?</p>

            <p>I have read a great <seg xml:id="h3174a" corresp="m01"
                  style="text-orientation: sideways-left">
                  <pb n="5" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_5.jpg"/> many of the stories in <choice><abbr>y<hi
                           rend="superscript"
                     >r</hi>.</abbr><expan>your</expan><expan>your</expan></choice> new book. Some
                  day I must talk</seg>
               <pb n="6" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_6.jpg"/>
               <seg xml:id="h3174b" corresp="m02" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">to you
                  about them. I thought the "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1913_AChangedManandOtherTales"
                     >Tryst at the Ancient Earthwork</ref>" <hi rend="underline">extremely</hi> good
                  - &amp; such a difficult thing to do! "<ref
                     target="#bib:Hardy1913_AChangedManandOtherTales">The Waiting Supper</ref>"
                     "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1913_AChangedManandOtherTales">The Grave by the
                     Handpost</ref>" - &amp; "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1913_AChangedManandOtherTales"
                     >A Mere Interlude</ref> are very characteristic of you – including that
                  dramatic</seg>
               <pb n="7" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_7.jpg"/>
               <seg xml:id="h3174c" corresp="m03" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">situation
                  of the honeymoon in the latter - The "<ref
                     target="#bib:Hardy1913_AChangedManandOtherTales">Committee Man of the
                     Terror</ref>" is very original &amp; I <hi rend="underline">so</hi> admire the
                  last paragraph "that outline against the stars of the morning" – is graphic –
                     "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1913_AChangedManandOtherTales">Alicia's Diary</ref>"
                  interested me – but in <hi rend="underline">some</hi> ways it is unlike you – I
                  think –?</seg>
               <pb n="8" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3174_8.jpg"/>
               <seg xml:id="h3174d" corresp="m04" style="text-orientation: sideways-left"> I hope
                  you are feeling better, &amp; the vein in <choice><abbr>y<hi rend="superscript"
                           >r</hi>.</abbr><expan>your</expan></choice> leg does not now give
                  trouble?</seg>
               <seg xml:id="h3174e" corresp="m05" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">This place
                  seems to suit me – &amp; I am doing a good deal to the garden &amp; I hope to
                  encourage many birds.</seg>
            </p>

            <closer xml:id="h3190f" corresp="m06" style="text=orientation: sideways-left">
               <salute><choice><abbr>y<hi rend="superscript"
                     >r</hi></abbr><expan>your</expan></choice>
                  <choice><abbr>affec.</abbr></choice> friend</salute>
               <signed>FH</signed>
            </closer>


         </div>
      </body>
